SIMPLE: cleat
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Cleat
<hw>Cleat</hw> <pr>(kl⟦emac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>clete</ets> wedge; cf. D. <ets>kloot</ets> ball, Ger.
<ets>kloss</ets>, <ets>klotz</ets>, lump. clod, MHG.
<ets>kl⟦omac⟧z</ets> lump, ball, wedge, OHG. <ets>chl⟦omac⟧z</ets> ball,
round mass.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Carp.)</fld> <def>A strip of wood or iron fastened
on transversely to something in order to give strength, prevent warping,
hold position, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A device made of wood or metal,
having two arms, around which turns may be taken with a line or rope so
as to hold securely and yet be readily released. It is bolted by the
middle to a deck or mast, etc., or it may be lashed to a rope.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cleat</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Cleat
<hw>Cleat</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To strengthen with a
cleat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cleavable</ent>⟦br⟧
